      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">How do entropy sources and CSPRNG work in seed generation?</p>
          <h2 id="a-entropy" >Entropy Sources and CSPRNG</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>BIP39 seed generation begins with a <strong>cryptographically secure pseudo-random number generator</strong> (CSPRNG). The quality of the entropy source is the foundation of the entire security model &mdash; if the randomness is predictable or biased, the resulting seed phrase is compromised regardless of word count.</p>
            <h3>Platform-Specific Entropy Sources</h3>
            <p>On modern systems, CSPRNGs are typically backed by operating system entropy pools:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><code>/dev/urandom</code> on Linux &mdash; draws from the kernel entropy pool seeded by hardware interrupts, disk timing, and other sources</li>
              <li><code>CryptGenRandom</code> / <code>BCryptGenRandom</code> on Windows &mdash; backed by the Windows CNG provider</li>
              <li><code>SecRandomCopyBytes</code> on macOS/iOS &mdash; Secure Enclave-backed on devices with the T2/M-series chip</li>
              <li><code>crypto.getRandomValues()</code> via the Web Crypto API in browsers &mdash; delegates to the OS CSPRNG</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Entropy Length and Word Count</h3>
            <p>The entropy length directly determines the mnemonic word count. Each additional 32 bits of entropy adds exactly 3 words and 1 checksum bit:</p>
            <div class="guide-table-wrap">
              <table class="guide-table guide-table--compact">
                <thead><tr><th>ENT (bits)</th><th>CS (bits)</th><th>Total bits</th><th>Words</th></tr></thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr><td class="num">128</td><td class="num">4</td><td class="num">132</td><td class="num">12</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="num">160</td><td class="num">5</td><td class="num">165</td><td class="num">15</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="num">192</td><td class="num">6</td><td class="num">198</td><td class="num">18</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="num">224</td><td class="num">7</td><td class="num">231</td><td class="num">21</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="num">256</td><td class="num">8</td><td class="num">264</td><td class="num">24</td></tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
            <p>The formula is: <code>CS = ENT / 32</code>, and <code>words = (ENT + CS) / 11</code>.</p>
            <div class="callout callout-warning">
              <span class="callout-label">Security Warning</span>
              Never generate entropy from user-chosen patterns, brain wallets, or low-entropy sources. Predictable inputs collapse the search space from 2<sup>128</sup> to a trivially brute-forceable range. Always use a CSPRNG.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">How does the SHA-256 checksum mechanism verify a seed phrase?</p>
          <h2 id="a-checksum" >SHA-256 Checksum Mechanism</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>After generating raw entropy, the system computes a <strong>SHA-256 hash</strong> of the entropy bytes. The first <em>N</em> bits of this hash (where <code>N = entropy_bits / 32</code>) are appended to the entropy as a checksum.</p>
            <h3>Step-by-Step Process</h3>
            <ol>
              <li>Generate <code>ENT</code> bits of random entropy (e.g., 128 bits)</li>
              <li>Compute <code>H = SHA-256(entropy_bytes)</code></li>
              <li>Take the first <code>ENT/32</code> bits of <code>H</code> as the checksum</li>
              <li>Concatenate: <code>entropy_bits || checksum_bits</code></li>
              <li>Split the result into 11-bit groups</li>
              <li>Map each 11-bit value to the corresponding BIP39 word</li>
            </ol>
            <blockquote><p>The checksum ensures that approximately 15 out of every 16 randomly chosen 12-word combinations (for 4-bit checksum) will be invalid. This error-detection capability catches accidental transcription mistakes during recovery, though it is not a security mechanism against deliberate attacks.</p></blockquote>
            <h3>Validation During Recovery</h3>
            <p>When a user enters a seed phrase for recovery, the wallet reverses the process: it converts words back to 11-bit indices, separates the checksum bits, recomputes the SHA-256 hash of the entropy portion, and verifies that the extracted checksum matches. A mismatch indicates a typo, missing word, or incorrect word order.</p>
            <div class="callout callout-info">
              <span class="callout-label">Technical Note</span>
              The checksum covers only data integrity, not authenticity. It cannot detect if the entropy source was weak or compromised. A valid checksum only means the word combination is structurally correct, not that the underlying randomness was sufficient.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">How is a master key derived from a mnemonic phrase?</p>
          <h2 id="a-derivation" >From Mnemonic to Master Key (BIP32/BIP44)</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>The mnemonic phrase is not used directly as a cryptographic key. Instead, it undergoes a key-stretching process to produce a <strong>512-bit seed</strong>, which then feeds into hierarchical deterministic key derivation.</p>
            <h3>PBKDF2 Key Stretching</h3>
            <p>The mnemonic string (space-separated words, UTF-8 NFKD-normalized) is passed through <code>PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA512</code> with <strong>2,048 iterations</strong>. The salt is the string <code>"mnemonic"</code> concatenated with an optional user-supplied <a href="<%= langPrefix %>/guides/passphrase#b-how-works">passphrase</a> (the "25th word"):</p>
            <div class="guide-code-block">
              <div class="guide-code-block__label">PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA512</div>
              <div class="guide-code-block__body"><span class="kw">seed</span> <span class="op">=</span> <span class="fn">PBKDF2</span><span class="op">(</span>
  <span class="kw">password</span><span class="op">:</span> mnemonic_string,     <span class="cm">// "abandon ability able ..."</span>
  <span class="kw">salt</span><span class="op">:</span>     <span class="st">"mnemonic"</span> + passphrase, <span class="cm">// "mnemonic" or "mnemonicMySecret"</span>
  <span class="kw">iterations</span><span class="op">:</span> <span class="nm">2048</span>,
  <span class="kw">dkLen</span><span class="op">:</span>    <span class="nm">64</span>,                  <span class="cm">// 512 bits</span>
  <span class="kw">PRF</span><span class="op">:</span>      <span class="fn">HMAC-SHA512</span>
<span class="op">)</span></div>
            </div>
            <p>The 2,048 iterations provide a deliberate computational cost that slows down brute-force attempts against weak passphrases, while remaining fast enough for legitimate use.</p>
            <h3>BIP32 Master Key Derivation</h3>
            <p>The 512-bit seed is fed into <code>HMAC-SHA512</code> with the key <code>"Bitcoin seed"</code>. The output is split into two 256-bit halves:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Left 256 bits</strong> &mdash; the master private key</li>
              <li><strong>Right 256 bits</strong> &mdash; the master chain code (used for child derivation)</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Derivation Paths (BIP44/BIP84/BIP86)</h3>
            <p>The master key feeds into BIP32 hierarchical deterministic key derivation. Standardized paths determine which specific key pair is generated for each coin and account:</p>
            <div class="guide-code-block">
              <div class="guide-code-block__label">Derivation Paths (BIP44 / BIP84 / BIP86)</div>
              <div class="guide-code-block__body"><span class="kw">m</span> <span class="op">/</span> <span class="kw">purpose'</span> <span class="op">/</span> <span class="kw">coin_type'</span> <span class="op">/</span> <span class="kw">account'</span> <span class="op">/</span> <span class="kw">change</span> <span class="op">/</span> <span class="kw">address_index</span></div>
            </div>
            <div class="guide-table-wrap">
              <table class="guide-table guide-table--compact">
                <thead><tr><th>Path</th><th>Standard</th><th>Address Type</th></tr></thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr><td class="mono">m/44'/0'/0'/0/0</td><td>BIP44</td><td>Bitcoin Legacy (P2PKH)</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="mono">m/44'/60'/0'/0/0</td><td>BIP44</td><td>Ethereum</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="mono">m/49'/0'/0'/0/0</td><td>BIP49</td><td>Bitcoin Nested SegWit (P2SH-P2WPKH)</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="mono">m/84'/0'/0'/0/0</td><td>BIP84</td><td>Bitcoin Native SegWit (P2WPKH)</td></tr>
                  <tr><td class="mono">m/86'/0'/0'/0/0</td><td>BIP86</td><td>Bitcoin Taproot (P2TR)</td></tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
            <p>Each path segment narrows from the master key to a specific purpose, coin, account, and address index. The apostrophe (<code>'</code>) indicates hardened derivation, which prevents child key compromise from leaking parent key information.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">How was the BIP39 wordlist designed?</p>
          <h2 id="a-wordlist" >Wordlist Design and Multilingual Support</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>The BIP39 English wordlist was engineered with strict constraints to minimize ambiguity and transcription errors across different contexts (handwriting, phone dictation, poor lighting):</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>4-character uniqueness</strong> &mdash; no two words share the same first four letters, enabling unambiguous abbreviation on constrained displays</li>
              <li><strong>Levenshtein distance</strong> &mdash; words were selected to maximize edit distance between similar entries, reducing confusion from single-character typos</li>
              <li><strong>Common vocabulary</strong> &mdash; obscure or easily misspelled words were excluded</li>
              <li><strong>ASCII-safe</strong> &mdash; no diacritics or special characters in the English list</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Non-English Wordlists</h3>
            <p>BIP39 includes official wordlists for multiple languages. Each wordlist is independently curated and contains exactly 2,048 words. Importantly, wordlists are <strong>not translations</strong> of each other &mdash; a seed generated with the English list cannot be recovered using the Japanese list. The wordlist used during generation must also be used during recovery.</p>
            <div class="callout callout-tip">
              <span class="callout-label">Compatibility Note</span>
              In practice, the English wordlist is the de facto standard. Most hardware wallets and popular software wallets only support the English list. If cross-wallet compatibility is important, stick with English.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section-block">
        <div class="container">
          <p class="section-question">What are the known attack vectors against seed phrases?</p>
          <h2 id="a-attacks" >Attack Vectors and Entropy Analysis</h2>
          <div class="guide-text">
            <p>Understanding the threat landscape for seed phrases helps calibrate security decisions. The primary attack vectors are:</p>
            <h3>Brute-Force Attacks</h3>
            <p>A 128-bit entropy seed (12 words) provides a search space of 2<sup>128</sup> &asymp; 3.4 &times; 10<sup>38</sup> possible keys. At 10 billion guesses per second (far beyond current capability for full key derivation), exhausting this space would take approximately 10<sup>21</sup> years. This is secure against any classical computing attack.</p>
            <h3>Partial Knowledge Attacks</h3>
            <p>If an attacker knows <em>some</em> words of your seed phrase, the remaining search space shrinks dramatically:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>11 of 12 words known</strong> &mdash; 2,048 candidates (trivially brute-forceable)</li>
              <li><strong>10 of 12 words known</strong> &mdash; ~4.2 million candidates (seconds to crack)</li>
              <li><strong>8 of 12 words known</strong> &mdash; ~1.76 &times; 10<sup>13</sup> candidates (days to weeks)</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="callout callout-warning">
              <span class="callout-label">Security Warning</span>
              Never split your seed phrase into parts thinking each part is independently secure. If an attacker obtains any significant portion, the remaining entropy may be brute-forceable. Use Shamir's Secret Sharing (SLIP39) instead for threshold-based backup splitting.
            </div>
            <h3>Side-Channel and Social Attacks</h3>
            <p>In practice, most seed phrase compromises do not involve brute-force. They come from phishing (fake wallet recovery pages), malware (clipboard hijacking, keyloggers), physical theft of backup material, and social engineering. Strong entropy is necessary but not sufficient &mdash; <a href="<%= langPrefix %>/guides/opsec#b-what-opsec">operational security</a> is equally critical.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>

    <!-- ===== FAQ SECTION ===== -->
    <section class="section-block faq-section">
      <div class="container">
        <p class="label">[ FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS ]</p>
        <h2 >FAQ</h2>
        <div class="faq-chat">

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Can I choose my own seed words instead of random ones?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="Technically you can construct a valid BIP39 mnemonic manually, but it is strongly discouraged. Humans are extremely poor at generating randomness &mdash; we gravitate toward patterns, familiar words, and predictable sequences. An attacker can exploit these biases to dramatically reduce the search space. Always use a CSPRNG-backed generator from a trusted wallet."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Is a 12-word seed phrase secure enough?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="A 12-word phrase provides 128 bits of entropy, which yields approximately 3.4 &times; 10^38 possible combinations. This exceeds the security level of AES-128, which is considered secure for classified government data. No known or theorized classical computer can brute-force 128 bits. Even accounting for future quantum computing, Grover's algorithm would only halve the effective security to 64 bits for key search &mdash; still formidable, and mitigated by the PBKDF2 key-stretching step. For most users, 12 words is more than sufficient."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>What happens if I lose one word from my seed phrase?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="If you know the position of the missing word, there are only 2,048 candidates to try. Specialized open-source tools can test all possibilities in seconds by checking the checksum and derived addresses against known balances. If you don't know the position, it becomes 12 &times; 2,048 = 24,576 attempts &mdash; still feasible. Losing two or more words makes recovery exponentially harder and may require significant computation."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Can I split my seed phrase between multiple locations?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="Naive splitting (e.g., words 1-6 in location A, words 7-12 in location B) is dangerous because each half has only 66 bits of entropy &mdash; well within brute-force range. A better approach is Shamir's Secret Sharing (SLIP39), which creates M-of-N shares where any M shares can reconstruct the secret, but fewer than M shares reveal zero information. This is mathematically proven to be information-theoretically secure."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>Are all 2,048 BIP39 words unique enough to avoid confusion?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="Yes. The BIP39 English wordlist was specifically curated so that each word is uniquely identifiable by its first four characters. For example, &quot;abandon&quot; and &quot;ability&quot; differ at character 3. This means even partial reading, abbreviated storage, or small-screen displays can distinguish any two words. Additionally, words with similar spelling or pronunciation were deliberately excluded from the list."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q-btn" type="button">
              <span>What is the difference between a seed phrase and a private key?</span>
              <span class="faq-arrow">&rsaquo;</span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-bubble-wrap">
              <div class="faq-bubble" data-text="A private key is a single 256-bit number that controls one specific address. A seed phrase, by contrast, is a human-readable representation of entropy that can derive an unlimited number of private keys through hierarchical deterministic (HD) derivation. Backing up one seed phrase protects all addresses across all supported cryptocurrencies. Backing up individual private keys is impractical and error-prone."></div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

